challenges.description:
Screen-space partial derivatives let a fragment shader measure how fast a value changes across neighboring pixels. HLSL calls them ddx()/ddy(); GLSL calls them dFdx()/dFdy().

Translate the HLSL edge-detection snippet below to GLSL. The shader computes how fast the UV coordinates change and uses that to draw sharp grid lines.

HLSL reference:
```hlsl
float2 uv;         // screen UVs scaled to [0, 10]
float2 dudv = float2(ddx(uv.x), ddy(uv.y));  // pixel-to-pixel UV delta
float2 grid = abs(frac(uv - 0.5) - 0.5) / dudv;
float  line = min(grid.x, grid.y);
float  val  = 1.0 - min(line, 1.0);
```

challenges.template:
uniform vec2 u_resolution;
out vec4 fragColor;

void main() {
    vec2 uv = gl_FragCoord.xy / u_resolution * 10.0;
    // Translate the HLSL derivative + grid logic to GLSL
    vec2 dudv = vec2(/* ddx */ (uv.x), /* ddy */ (uv.y));
    vec2 grid = abs(fract(uv - 0.5) - 0.5) / dudv;
    float line = min(grid.x, grid.y);
    float val  = 1.0 - min(line, 1.0);
    fragColor = vec4(vec3(val), 1.0);
}

